Kaggle INGV Volcanic Eruption Prediction

Predicting a volcano’s next eruption using Machine Learning

From October 2020 to January 2021, the Italy’s Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia (INGV) hosted a competition on Kaggle that tasked data scientists to predict when a volcano’s next eruption will occur by analyzing a dataset collected by sensors deployed around active volcanoes. As a school project, we attempted to get a decent score in this competition, this article will walk you through our approach. 


·   ·   ·

Dataset Analysis

We started by loading the dataset provided for the competition in a pandas dataframe and looking at the data, we have 10 columns, one for each sensor.

dataframe.head()

Their values are all numeric and can be negative or positive, we can also see that some portions of the data are missing.

After some preliminary testing with a small regressor we decided to add some variants of our columns to our dataframe.

We started by writing a function to add 7 transformations per feature.

#Feature definition
def agg_stats(df, idx):
    df = df.agg(['sum', 'min', "mean", "std", "median", "skew", "kurtosis"])
    df_flat = df.stack()
    df_flat.index = df_flat.index.map('{0[1]}_{0[0]}'.format)
    df_out = df_flat.to_frame().T
    df_out["segment_id"] = int(idx)
    return df_out

This made us search for a way to get even more transformations, by exploiting the relations between the features and implementing various functions to get the most out of the data.

This is when we found the dataset INGV_TSFresh_7730 from Alexander Lyubchenko who expanded the data to 7731 columns for each sensors.

We loaded this dataframe, took a look inside and felt like we were ready to work with it.

Preprocess and Data Cleaning

After having loaded the new dataset, we had to come up with a solution to select only the most relevant features to reduce the number of columns.

Firstly, we defined a RandomForestRegressor, trained it on the dataset and used “model.feature_importances_” to have an array with the feature’s name in one column and its calculated importance in another.

x = train_rf.drop('time_to_eruption', axis=1)
y = train_rf['time_to_eruption']
#We train a simple model to estimate the importances of the columns.
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
model = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1, max_depth=7)
model.fit(x,y)

We started by using a subjective approach by choosing to keep the most important 350 features, we then decided to keep only the features that had an importance value over 0.001, letting us with 133 columns.

In this new dataset, the missing values are still present and we need to replace them with usable values. To accomplish this, we used “fillna()” on our dataframe and filled it with the “mode()” of our dataframe, this fills the missing data with the values that appear the most often.

# .fillna() fill up the missing values
# .model() return a set of the most common values in the dataset
all_data = all_data.fillna(all_data.mode())

Finally, to continue optimizing our dataset, we decided to reduce the numbers of variables to work with a “simpler” dataset, to achieve that, we used PCA.

Principal Component Analysis or PCA is a dimensionality reduction method used to reduce the dimensionality of a large data sets, there’s a common problem in machine learning known as the Curse of dimensionality.

This expression was coined by Richard Bellman in 1961 to refer to the fact that

“Many algorithms that work fine in low dimensions become intractable when the input is high-dimensional.”

We use PCA to counter this problem, by reducing the number of variables of the dataset, while preserving as much information as possible.

After we felt that the dataset was optimized enoughn we started loading our model and started the training.

LightGBM Model Training

For the model, we’ve choosed to use LightGBM which is a gradient boosting framework, “gradient boosting” is a machine learning technique for regression and classification problem which produces a prediction model in the form of an ensemble of weak prediction models, typically decision trees.

import lightgbm as lgb
from lightgbm import LGBMRegressorgbm =lgb.LGBMRegressor(
learning_rate=0.04,
max_depth=5,          #hyperparameters from clf.best_params_
n_estimators=2000, 
num_leaves=26) 
gbm.fit(train, target)

We used GridSearchCV for the hyperparameter tuning of the model, GridSearch is an algorithm trying out every combinations of the model hyperparameters from an array of arrays where all the values are stored.

After trying all combinations, the GridSearch will return the “best_params_” value, containing the optimal parameters.

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCVY = target
X = train
grid_params = {
    'num_leaves': [24, 25, 26],
    'learning_rate': [0.04, 0.05, 0.06],
    'max_depth': [4, 5, 6],
    'n_estimators': [1000, 1500, 2000]
}clf = GridSearchCV(lgb.LGBMRegressor(), grid_params, scoring='r2')
clf.fit(X, Y)print("Best parameters set found on development set:")
print(clf.best_params_)

In search for better accuracy, we ran the GridSearch a couple of times to pinpoint the optimal values by framing the best_params and running it again.

Performance Analysis

To evaluate how our model is doing, we’re using a metric called

“Mean squared error regression loss”

It measures the average of the squares of the errors — that is, the average squared difference between the estimated values and the actual values.

This allows us to have a clue as to what direction we are taking and to differentiate an improvement from a degradation.

Possible way of improvement

This project is still far from finished as we only got in the middle of the leaderboard as of now.

Even though we are happy with our results, a lot could possibly be done to greatly improve our pipeline, we could potentially improve the quality of our prediction by trying to run the model with even less features especially after we sorted them out by “importance”, we could also try other regression models and scoring metrics.

We might also try using the GridSearch on a bit more parameters to have a way more specific and precise model tuning.
